QHttp is asynchronous. You don't need threads. And in fact it works better if you DON'T use a thread. Sure, so why are you using a thread? QHttp doesn't block on requests. Not very easily. You should have it start the request and use the finished signal to trigger the next step. You can SIMULATE blocking behavior by using my QSignalWaiter class but it's far cleaner to use the signals and slots the way they're intended. cplusplus: Use a QBuffer as the QIODevice for the response data, then when the finished signal is emitted, handle it and start your next request. It's a QIODevice for a QByteArray Well, you see QHttp::request() has a QIODevice*to parameter? Use a QBuffer in it and the response from the request will be stored in it. Putting webapp classes in the common/ tree is usually bad form. That's for classes that you want to be available to both the Tomcat servlet container and to your webapp. The shared/ tree is for classes shared between 2 or more webapps. So, if you're developing just one webapp, you should try to put all your classes under your webapp's WEB-INF/classes and/or WEB-INF/lib, or configure a custom loader for your webapp's Context that has other paths in it.

3aa4c68c2ceb0521f6c25f50e2e0950e: Did you want to track flexbox issues in Tracker or the wiki? 'Cuz Alex seems to be very interested in sorting that out, and it's probably a good idea now that you're actively working on the spec Tracker is pretty straightforward. If you look around, I'm sure you can figure it out. Its main advantages are integration with IRC and the mailing lists. It's main disadvantages are sub-optimal web interface and only editable by WG members. Another advantage is a better archiving story: issues each have their own page, so the URL is stable even when they're purged from the currently active list thinks about usage patterns I think I tend to use Tracker for pre-LCWD issues for that very reason. They let me focus on what's open and ignore what's closed But for LC comments, I track those in a plaintext file, since I want the whole list, open and closed, available. keeps that file in CVS, along with the spec

I'm trying to understand why port forwarding is done a certain way. The rules that I supposedly have to add are: iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -d <external IP> -p tcp --dport 80 -j DNAT --to-destination <internal IP of HTTP server> iptables -t nat -A OUTPUT -d <external IP> -p tcp --dport 80 -j DNAT --to-destination <internal IP of HTTP server> iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -s <internal IP address range> -d <internal IP of HTTP server> -p tcp --dport 80 -j SNAT --to-source <internal IP of NAT box> The offered rationale is: rule 1 lets external IPs (from the Internet) reach the HTTP server, rule 2 lets the NAT box reach the HTTP server, and rule 3 lets internal IPs (from the home network) reach the HTTP server via its external address. Rule 1 and 2 seem to be simple substitution. Just replace the destination with the right internal IP before routing. Rule 3 is giving me a headache. It's not that it doesn't work (I don't have a HTTP server up yet to try it, I'm just trying to understand), I'm just having trouble understanding how it's supposed to work. Why is it in rule 3 that the desination is the /internal/ IP of the HTTP server? Shouldn't it be the external IP, like all the other rules? That's what we'd be trying to contact right? Why do we point it at the internal IP of the NAT box? I assume this is some why of returning packets where they wouldn't normally go, so it can send it back along some NAT chain? Yes I've looked at the diagram. I can see that stuff floats in from the internet interface. Then goes to the mangle table prerouting chain, then the nat table prerouting chain. It hits rule 1, then gets passed off to the HTTP server. Due to DNAT "remembering" who started a stream, I assume that's all it needs to get back out to the internet (i.e. my masquerade/SNAT rule in the nat table postrouting chain is not applied?). blumber, if you'll wait a few minutes I think I can answer your question Hmm, let me look at the diagram again... So this means that any given connection can only possibly hit /one/ NAT chain, right? Hmm... Well, I can see how hitting rule 1 (DNAT), and my masquerading/SNAT rule (not shown), wouldn't hurt anything, since it all ends up pretending to be from the NAT box address anyway. Since you've been waiting around a bit blumber I'll take a shot at answering your question... From what I can tell, netfilter remembers what packets go with what connection (hence the term connection tracking). You've got many internal IPs, and only one external. So all replies go to the external IP (there's no other possability), hence you don't need something in the prerouting chain. But you need something in the postrouting chain, because you have lots of separate internal IPs trying to use the same external IPs, and you need something to keep straight who's connected to what, and that "thing" is either masquerade or source network address translation. The diagram helps a lot, showing what goes through what chains when. Outgoing packets never see the prerouting chain. So again, you don't need anything special for them to share an IP. They /do/ see the postrouting chain, so, again, you need masquerade or SNAT there. Did that answer your question? danielg: On this first packet thing... If the NAT table only sees the first packet, how can it be both DNAT'ed and SNAT'ed? Can you use DNAT or SNAT somewhere other than the NAT table? There obviously can't be more than one "first" packet. blumber: Well, here's what's happening. Let's say you have external IP 111.111.111.111 (please just pretend). Internally you have computers 192.168.0.2 and 192.168.0.3 behind your NAT box. The NAT box is 192.168.0.1 as far as they're concerned. So the computer with the network interface card with the IP 192.168.0.2 says, I wanna look at http://www.stuff.com/ The packet slips into 192.168.0.1's mangle prerouting chain, nat prerouting chain, mangle forward chain, mangle filtering chain, and mangle postrouting chain. And so far (since you have no fancy pants rules) nothing happens. [Again, you may have fancy pants rules, please just play along.] But the last thing it hits, is the nat postrouting chain, where it meets your masquerade or SNAT rule, that makes everything look like it's coming from 111.111.111.111 rather than 192.168.0.2 which is the computer that made the request! So then it floats out onto the internet and ends up finding its way to www.stuff.com www.stuff.com packages its webpage up in packets and sends it off to 111.111.111.111 since that's, as far as it can tell, where the connection came from (remember your masquerade/SNAT rule). So the packets arrive at 111.111.111.111 and your NAT box says "golly, I do believe someone was asking for packets from www.stuff.com". It looks up in its data structures who that was, and finds 192.168.0.2. Then passes them back to 192.168.0.2 on your internal network. And we all lived happily ever after. Did that help? :) Well, I'm not real clear on that myself, but let's pretend they did. Further, let's pretend you don't have any nat prerouting rules. Because you don't need them. You're not trying to split out incoming connections. All you're trying to do is join outgoing ones. You don't need any prerouting rules. You /do/ need a nat postrouting rule to join those connections, so everything looks like it's coming from 111.111.111.111 no matter how many computers you have on your home network (or whatever). Uh... There is no QMainWidget That's a Qt3 guide and you're using Qt4. Use the Qt4 tutorials. That's exactly what it is; setMainWidget is a Qt3 function that's no longer needed in Qt4. The Blanchette book, yeah, we know. That's where all of the Qt3 programmers in here come from. :P Yeah, the one in Assistant or on doc.trolltech.com/4.1 is really good. Just work through the tutorial and you'll learn everything you need. (Assistant and the site are the same files) Yeah, that's the Qt3 stuff. The Qt4 book by the same author hasn't been released in PDF yet, but you can buy the book at a bookstore. There IS another Qt4 book online: http://cartan.cas.suffolk.edu/moin/OopDocbook QMainWindow isn't even the same thing. Qt3's setMainWidget means that when the main widget is closed, the app terminates. Qt4 doesn't need it because when all top-level widgets are closed, the app terminates. Also, looking at the code there, I can once again reaffirm my earlier statement about QMetaObject::connectSlotsByName() It connects signals from named objects in the current object to the appropriately-named slots in the object in the parameter list. (For a multiple-inheritance object, you use "this" so both are the same object.) Actually, thinking about that more, it's actually even smarter than THAT It doesn't use the "current object" because it's a static function -- it doesn't know about the "current object." Rather, setupUi() sets the parent for each widget to the parent widget, and the connectSlotsByName function simply connects all named children of the specified object to the appropriate slots. skyphyr: Any luck? 2b8cbb4405aaf8e4700ed53266152630: So one problm with your example is that it doesn't really work If you say date of birth [DD/MM/YYYY] but the browser only accepts MM/DD/YYYY input, people will get stuff wrong It has to submit dates in ISO format The UI can accept anything It is totally fine to have a UI that accepts the string "yesterday", for example I am concerned with the situation where the page author makes assumptions about the format based on their local testing That aren't valid for their users and then use that to write placeholder text Of course it can be safe if you can also specify the format that any text entry should accept. But that could break consistency between sites in the same UA

b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: not sure I follow ‚Äî why would the browser only accept that format? I thought the spec mandates that it has to accept ISO 8601 formatted dates? I'm not sure what you mean by ‚Äòif you say date of birth [DD/MM/YYYY]‚Äô ‚Äî do you mean, if I were to specify a dateformat attribute of that format? so you're concerned about a situation where the UA accepts a given format, but the element is displaying a different format? maybe I wasn't clear enough ‚Äî the dateformat attribute I'm suggesting is purely for display, not for entry yeah, that makes sense. nods so, although existing implementations of input[type=date] use ISO format for entry, there is no reason why they should always do this, and so using that format as placeholder text could create broken expectations. that is a valid reason to be concerned. curiously enough, if the browser doesn't support input[type=date] but does support placeholders, you'll get the desired effect by mandating (say) ISO formatted date strings, and giving a placeholder value alongside it. but as soon as the browser supports that type, it'll (potentially) break annoying.

wonders if it'd be interesting to see what strings <acronym> and <abbr> are currently used for, to see if they're just interchangable in practice, or if it's best to stay far away from the whole topic The main problem is that people who say they do know the difference disagree on what the difference is :-) Wikipedia says "The word acronym was coined during the mid-20th century for abbreviations pronounced as words, such as NATO and AIDS." That's what I mean about people disagreeing Screen readers are only helped if <acronym> is used mostly correctly, and if it's better to trust the markup than to guess, and it doesn't seem clear that that's the case should probably expand his collection of pages so there's a more useful amount of data Do any treat them differently to <span>? There's http://philip.html5.org/data/abbr-acronym.txt of quite limited usefulness or quality They're almost all http://www.imusic.dk/ It looks like it wouldn't be good for a screen reader to try pronouncing <acronym>s as single words not to read out the individual letters which leaves them with zero good options s/not/nor/ happens to see http://friendlybit.com/html/encyclopedia-of-html-elements/ saying "ACRONYM: No need to use this one, abbr is enough. Do we really need to differ between acronyms and abbreviations? What about initialisms and the other types of words?"

The main problem with asking people to distinguish between <acronym> and <abbr> is that they don't know what the difference is (that is to say, an acronym is read out as the letters, like RSPCA, whereas an abbreviation is said, like NATO). I myself advocate keeping <acronym> around and saying people SHOULD use <acronym> for acronyms, but MAY use <abbr> if they don't know the difference. This is the friendliest solution for Web developers, but for developers of e.g. screen reading software it's pretty nightmarish. Unfortunately that's not modern usage. =P I was taught acronyms are read out as letters. I don't disagree there. So I suppose that's the strongest argument you can give for dropping <acronym> altogether. But I think keeping <acronym> around but allowing unconditional use of <abbr> is marginally friendlier to the makers of screen readers etc.
Is there anyone who disagrees that an acronym is also an abbreviation, regardless of what an acronym is defined to be?
Do any existing screenreaders treat <abbr> differently from <acronym>? That's part of what I'm wondering :-)
